{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2017}} {{Use British English|date=October 2017}} {{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->
| name = Jim Radford | background = solo_singer | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1928|10|1|df=y}} | birth_place = [[Kingston upon Hull|Hull]], [[East Riding of Yorkshire]], [[England]] | genre = [[Folk music|Folk]], [[Sea shanty|Maritime music]] }}
'''Jim Radford''' is a British folk singer and songwriter, peace campaigner and political and community activist. He is also the youngest known participant in the [[invasion of Normandy|Allied invasion of Normandy]] in June 1944.
Jim Radford was a well-known figure in the British Peace Movement and anti-war campaigns in the 1960s and 1970s (particularly in the [[Campaign for Nuclear Disarmament]], and the British campaign against the USA's [[Vietnam War]]). He was also prominent in [[Direct Action]] Housing campaigns (e.g. the King Hill Hostel campaign of the mid 1960s, the [[Squatting in England and Wales|Family Squatting Associations]] in London in the late 1960s and early 1970s<ref>Bailey, Ron; The Squatters (1973) Penguin:UK {{ISBN|0140523006}}</ref><ref>Curtis, Helen and Sanderson, Mimi; The Unsung Sixties; 2004 (pp 1 to 18); Whiting & Birch: {{ISBN|1861770448}}</ref> and the occupation of [[Centre Point]] in Central London in 1974). He gained renewed prominence in 2014 when it was discovered by the [[BBC]] and the [[Royal British Legion]] that not only was he the youngest allied veteran of the Normandy invasion but that he had written a memorable song about his experiences as a young seaman on one of the Deep Sea Tugs that built the [[Mulberry Harbour]] at [[Arromanches-les-Bains|Arromanches]] ([[Gold Beach]]) – and he could sing. Radford performed his song, ''The Shores of Normandy'', three times at the [[Royal Albert Hall]] in London in the 70th anniversary year of the invasion (2014) and two of these concerts were televised by the BBC (the BBC's own 70th anniversary commemoration event in June<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DsVQMfxIfks |title=Jim Radford - The Shores of Normandy |publisher=[[YouTube]] |date=2010-11-16 |accessdate=2016-11-22}}</ref> and the British Legion Remembrance Day concert in November<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HsjeIW0I46Q |title=Shores of Normandy - Jim Radford |publisher=[[YouTube]] |date=2014-11-11 |accessdate=2016-11-22}}</ref>).
Jim Radford went to sea at fifteen when he sailed from his home-town of [[Kingston upon Hull|Hull]] in the East Riding of Yorkshire in the spring of 1944 as a [[Galley (kitchen)|galley boy]] on the ''[[Empire Larch]]''.<ref>The story of how he managed to get a berth on an ocean going ship at fifteen, when this was supposedly prohibited by war-time regulations, is told in Radford's own words in the 2007 documentary film ''Mayday Tugs of War'' by US film-maker Robin Williams {{cite web|url=http://www.maydaytugsofwar.com/trailers/meetjimr.html |title=Mayday Tugs of War |publisher=Mayday Tugs of War |date= |accessdate=2016-11-22}}</ref> The ''Empire Larch'' was a Deep Sea Tug owned by the British [[Ministry of War Transport]]<ref>Dear, I. 'The Tattie Lads' (London: Bloomsbury, 2016), {{ISBN|978-1-8448-6401-0}}</ref> and engaged in war work (assembling the convoy of block-ships for Operation Corn Cob<ref>Operation 'Corn Cob' was an enormous maritime engineering operation involving the precise positioning and scuttling of dozens of 'blockships' to form breakwaters and provide calmer water on the invasion beaches. Two of these artificial breakwaters (at Omaha and Gold beaches) were then used to shelter the construction of [[Mulberry harbour]]s. The ''Empire Larch'' arrived at ''Gold Beach'' with part of this convoy on the evening of 6 June 1944 while fighting was still going on around the beachhead. See the section on Breakwaters in the Wikipedia [[Mulberry harbour]] page.</ref>) in preparation for the invasion of France. He joined the Royal Navy on turning 18 and settled back on dry land in 1954, becoming an activist in various humanist, political and Peace Campaigns and helping to organise the first of the [[Aldermaston Marches]] in 1958 (later adopted by the [[Campaign for Nuclear Disarmament]]) and being invited to join the [[Committee of 100 (United Kingdom)|Committee of 100]] shortly after its foundation in 1960.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sro.sussex.ac.uk/6910/ |author=Carroll, Sam|title='Fill the jails': identity, structure and method in the Committee of 100, 1960 – 1968 : Sussex Research Online|quotation=This DPhil thesis includes interviews with Radford and other activists of the time|website=Sro.sussex.ac.uk |date= |accessdate=2016-11-22}}</ref> He retired after a varied career which included time as an Engineering Worker, in [[Fleet Street]], as a Press Officer, as Warden (Director) of [[Settlement movement|Blackfriars Settlement]] in South London,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blackfriars-settlement.org.uk/ |title=Welcome to Blackfriars Settlement |website=Blackfriars-settlement.org.uk |date= |accessdate=2016-11-22}}</ref> as General Secretary of Manchester [[Council for Voluntary Service]] and in various roles in Community Work and Social Action initiatives. He is a regular attender and performer at maritime and folk music festivals around the UK and although he is best known for his sea-songs and shanties (sung a cappella) he also sings from an extensive repertoire of British and Irish (and some Australian) folk songs as well as political and protest songs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.offbeat.karoo.net/shantyman |title=Jim Radford |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130825104922/http://www.offbeat.karoo.net/shantyman |archivedate=25 August 2013}}</ref> Radford also remains actively involved in the British section of the [[Veterans for Peace]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://veteransforpeace.org.uk/ |title=Veterans for Peace|website=Veteransforpeace.org.uk |date= |accessdate=2016-11-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=t0cjLndbzNw |title=Jim Radford in Los Angeles |publisher=[[YouTube]] |date=2015-08-04 |accessdate=2016-11-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://veteransforpeace.org.uk/2015/film-the-missing-peace/ |title=Film: The Missing Peace |website=Veteransforpeace.org.uk |date=2015-12-29 |accessdate=2016-11-22}}</ref> organisation. In October 2015 Radford was appointed a Chevalier of the [[Légion d'Honneur]]<ref>'Folk singer gets France's top gong' South London Press, 21 November 2015</ref> by the French Republic "in recognition of... steadfast involvement in the Liberation of France during the Second World War".<ref>Extract from the letter of citation from the French Consul which accompanied the medal</ref>
The first song Jim Radford wrote himself is also his most successful and best known, having been performed by him at two televised concerts at the [[Royal Albert Hall]].
Jim Radford is one of three brothers who all went to sea as teenagers and sailed as [[Merchant navy|Merchant Seamen]] during WWII (his eldest brother, 'Jack', qualified as a Radio Officer at just 17 and is thought to have been the youngest Merchant Navy Officer killed by enemy action in WWII when his ship, the ''SS Cree'', was torpedoed in November 1940,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uboat.net/allies/merchants/ships/662.html |title=Cree (British Steam merchant) - Ships hit by German U-boats during WWII |website=Uboat.net |date=1940-11-22 |accessdate=2016-11-22}}</ref> just weeks after his eighteenth birthday). Radford's tribute song to the wartime Merchant Navy, "The Merchant Seaman", won the Festival on the Moor<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.festivalonthemoor.co.uk/ |title=Festival on the Moor |publisher=Festival on the Moor |date= |accessdate=2016-11-22}}</ref> 'best song award' in 2009.
