[[File:Rolls Royce Phantom - Flickr - Alexandre Prévot (5) (cropped).jpg|thumb|250px|[[Rolls-Royce Phantom VII]] is a [[luxury vehicle]]]]
In [[economics]], a '''luxury good''' (or '''upmarket good''') is a [[good (economics)|good]] for which [[demand (economics)|demand]] increases more than proportionally as [[income]] rises, and is a contrast to a "[[necessity good]]", where demand increases proportionally less than income.<ref>{{cite book |first=Hal |last=Varian |authorlink=Hal Varian |title=Microeconomic Analysis |location=New York |publisher=W.W. Norton |edition=Third |year=1992 |isbn=0-393-95735-7 |chapter=Choice |pages=116–143 [p. 117] |quote=[...] as the consumer gets more income, he consumes more of both goods but proportionally more of one good (the ''luxury good'') than of the other (the ''necessary good''). |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=m20iQAAACAAJ&pg=PA117 }}</ref> ''Luxury goods'' is often used synonymously with ''[[superior good]]s'' and ''[[Veblen good]]s''.
The word "luxury" originated from the Latin word “Luxus,” which means indulgence of the senses, regardless of cost.<ref>{{cite journal|last1= Salehzadeh|first1= Reza|last2= Pool|first2= Javad|date= 19 Oct 2016|title= Brand Attitude and Perceived Value and Purchase Intention toward Global Luxury Brands|url= http://www.tandfonline.com/loi/wicm20|journal= Journal of International Consumer Marketing|volume= 29|issue= 2|pages= 74-82|doi= 10.1080/08961530.2016.1236311}}</ref>
==Market characteristics== {{unreferenced|section|date=March 2018}} [[Image:Patek-Philippe MG 2586.jpg|250px|left|thumb|[[Patek Philippe]] is a luxury watch brand]] [[File:Foie gras with sauternes.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Wine and [[foie gras]] ]]
Luxury goods are said to have high [[income elasticity of demand]]: as people become wealthier, they will buy more luxury goods. This also means, however, that should there be a decline in income its demand will drop. Income elasticity of demand is not constant with respect to income, and may change sign at different levels of income. That is to say, a luxury good may become a [[normal good]] or even an [[inferior good]] at different income levels, e.g. a wealthy person stops buying increasing numbers of [[luxury cars]] for his or her automobile collection to start collecting airplanes (at such an income level, the luxury car would become an inferior good).
Some luxury products have been claimed to be examples of [[Veblen good]]s, with a positive [[price elasticity of demand]]: for example, making a perfume more expensive can increase its perceived value as a luxury good to such an extent that sales can go up, rather than down.
Although the technical term luxury good is independent of the goods' quality, they are generally considered to be goods at the highest end of the market in terms of quality and price. Classic luxury goods include [[haute couture]] clothing, accessories, and luggage. Many markets have a luxury segment including, for example, [[automobile]], [[yacht]], [[wine]], [[bottled water]], [[coffee]], [[tea]], [[foods]], [[watches]], [[clothes]], [[jewelry]], and [[high fidelity]].
Luxuries may be services. The hiring of full-time or live-in [[domestic worker|domestic servants]] is a luxury reflecting disparities of income. Some financial services, especially in some brokerage houses, can be considered luxury services by default because persons in lower-income brackets generally do not use them.
Luxury goods often have special [[Luxury packaging]] to differentiate the products from mainstream competitors.
==Market trends== The three dominant trends are the main factors that have accelerated the rapid growth of the industry, including the customer base and variations in the consumptions of different brands.<ref name=":0">{{Cite journal|last1=Seo|first1=Yuri|last2=Oliver|first2=Margo Buchanan|date=2015|title=Luxury branding: the industry, trends, and future conceptualisations|url=https://doi.org/10.1108/APJML-10-2014-0148|journal=Asia Pacific Journal of Marketing and Logistics|volume=27(1)|pages=82-98|via=}}</ref> The three dominant trends in the global luxury goods market are [[globalization]], [[Consolidation (business)|consolidation]], and [[Diversification (marketing strategy)|diversification]].{{citation needed|date=March 2018}} Consolidation involves the growth of big companies and ownership of brands across many segments of luxury products. Examples include [[LVMH]], [[Richemont]], and [[Kering]], which dominate the market in areas ranging from luxury drinks to fashion and cosmetics.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.businessoffashion.com/articles/professional/lvmh-kering-richemont-where-to-place-your-bets|title=LVMH, Kering, Richemont? Where to Place Your Bets.|date=2016-06-13|work=The Business of Fashion|access-date=2018-07-28|language=en-GB}}</ref> Global consumer companies, such as [[Procter & Gamble]], are also attracted to the industry, due to the difficulty of making a [[profit (accounting)|profit]] in the mass consumer goods market.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2013-10-28/procter-and-gamble-profits-from-high-end-products|title=Procter & Gamble Cleans Up With Luxury Paper Towels|work=Bloomberg.com|access-date=2018-07-28|language=en}}</ref> The customer base for various luxury goods continue to be more culturally diversified, and this presents more unseen challenges and new opportunities to companies in this industry.<ref name=":0" />
==Market size==
The luxury goods market has been on an upward climb for many years. Apart from the setback caused by the [[1997 Asian Financial Crisis]], the industry has performed well, particularly in 2000. In that year, the world luxury goods market&nbsp;– which includes drinks, fashion, cosmetics, fragrances, watches, jewelry, luggage, handbags&nbsp;– was worth close to $170 billion and grew 7.9 percent.<ref>[http://www.library.yorku.ca/eresolver/?id=984257 “The World Market for Luxury Goods.” Global Market for Luxury Goods. Nov 1, 2001, March 5, 2007].</ref> The United States has been the largest regional market for luxury goods and is estimated to continue to be the leading personal luxury goods market in 2013, with a value of 62.5 billion euros.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Topic: Global Luxury Goods Industry|url = http://www.statista.com/topics/1110/global-luxury-goods-industry/|website = www.statista.com|accessdate = 2015-10-20}}</ref> The largest sector in this category was luxury drinks, including premium [[whisky]], [[Champagne (wine)|Champagne]], [[Cognac (drink)|Cognac]]. This sector was the only one that suffered a decline in value (-0.9 percent).{{citation needed|date=March 2018}} The watches and jewelry section showed the strongest performance, growing in value by 23.3 percent, while the clothing and accessories section grew 11.6 percent between 1996 and 2000, to $32.8 billion. North America is the largest regional market for luxury goods.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}} The largest ten markets for luxury goods account for 83 percent of overall sales, and include Japan, China, United States, Russia, Germany, Italy, France, United Kingdom, Brazil, Spain, and Switzerland.{{citation needed|date=February 2013}}
In 2012, [[Economy of China|China]] surpassed [[Economy of Japan|Japan]] as the world's largest luxury market.<ref>{{cite web|title=China bans television ads for bling|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2013/02/08/business/china-bans-luxury-product-ads/index.html?hpt=hp_bn5|accessdate=February 15, 2013}}</ref> China's luxury consumption accounts for over 25% of the global market.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.export-to-china.com/chinaWants/luxury|title=Export to China|work=export-to-china.com|accessdate=18 March 2015}}</ref> [[The Economist Intelligence Unit]] published a report on the outlook for luxury goods in Asia<ref>[http://www.eiu.com/public/topical_report.aspx?campaignid=AsiaLuxuryGoods Asia Luxury Goods]</ref> which explores the trends and forecasts for the luxury goods market across key markets in Asia. In 2014, the luxury sector is expected to grow over the next 10 years because of 440 million consumers spending a total of 880 billion euros, or $1.2 trillion.<ref name="Luxe Spending to Grow to $1.2 Trillion">{{cite web | url=http://www.wwd.com/business-news/forecasts-analysis/luxe-spending-to-grow-to-12-trillion-7399091?src=nl/mornReport/20140129 | title=Luxe Spending to Grow to $1.2 Trillion | publisher=WWD | date=28 January 2014 | accessdate=29 January 2014 | last=Zargani |first=Luisa}}</ref>
==Art history== {{unreferenced|section|date=March 2018}} [[File:Ballbüchlein Griot KGM 66-142.jpg|thumb|Secular [[Rococo]] luxury or [[treasure binding]] for a book, using techniques from the making of gold boxes, in gold, [[mother of pearl]] and hardstone, Berlin, 1750–1760. By this time such lavish bindings were unusual.]] Though often verging on the meaningless in modern marketing, "luxury" remains a legitimate{{clarify|date=March 2018}} and current technical term in [[art history]] for objects that are especially highly decorated to very high standards and use expensive materials. The term is especially used for [[medieval]] [[manuscript]]s to distinguish between practical working books for normal use, and fully [[illuminated manuscript]]s, that were often bound in [[treasure binding]]s with metalwork and jewels. These are often much larger, with less text on each page and many illustrations, and if [[liturgical text]]s were originally usually kept on the [[Altar in the Catholic Church|altar]] or [[sacristy]] rather any library that the church or [[monastery]] who owned them may have had. Secular luxury manuscripts were commissioned by the very wealthy and differed in the same ways from cheaper books.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}
"Luxury" may be used for other [[applied arts]] where both utilitarian and luxury versions of the same types of objects were made. This might cover metalwork, ceramics, glass, arms and armour, and a wide range of objects. It is much less used for objects with no function beyond being an artwork: paintings, drawings and [[sculpture]], even though the disparity in cost between an expensive and cheap work may have been as large.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}
==Scope of the term== With increasing "democratization" of luxury goods,<ref>{{cite journal |last=Wong |first=N. Y. |last2=Ahuvia |first2=A. C. |year=1998 |title=Personal taste and family face: Luxury consumption in Confucian and Western societies |journal=Psychology & Marketing |volume=15 |issue=5 |pages=423–441 |doi=10.1002/(SICI)1520-6793(199808)15:5<423::AID-MAR2>3.0.CO;2-9 }}</ref> new product categories have been created within the luxury market, called "accessible luxury" or "mass luxury". These are meant specifically for the [[middle class]], which sometimes called the "aspiring class" in this context. Because luxury has now diffused into the masses, defining the word has become more difficult.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pauravshukla.com/what-is-luxury |title=What is luxury? |publisher=Paurav Shukla |date=2010-05-14 |accessdate=2010-08-09}}</ref>
Bringing up to the modern day the long and generally very unsuccessful history of [[sumptuary law]]s designed to curb excessive personal consumption, in February 2013, the Chinese government banned advertisements for luxury goods on its official state radio and television channels.<ref>{{cite news|first=Ramy |last=Inocencio|title=China bans television ads for bling|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2013/02/08/business/china-bans-luxury-product-ads/index.html?hpt=hp_bn5|work=CNN|date=February 8, 2013|accessdate=February 15, 2013}}</ref>
==Socioeconomic significance== {{see also|positional good}} Several manufactured products attain the status of "luxury goods" due to their design, quality, durability or performance that are remarkably superior to the comparable substitutes.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Parker|first1=Christopher J.|last2=Doyle|first2=Stephen|editor1-last=Ozuem|editor1-first=Wilson|editor2-last=Azemi|editor2-first=Yllka|title=Designing Indulgent Interaction: Luxury Fashion, M-Commerce, and Übermensch|date=2018|publisher=IGI Global|location=1|isbn=9781522526971|pages=1-21|url=https://www.igi-global.com/gateway/chapter/191070|language=English|chapter=1}}</ref> Thus, virtually every category of goods available on the market today includes a subset of similar products whose "luxury" is marked by better-quality components and materials, solid construction, stylish appearance, increased durability, better performance, advanced features, and so on. As such, these luxury goods may retain or improve the basic functionality for which all items of a given category are originally designed.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}
There are also goods that are perceived as luxurious by the public simply because they play a role of [[status symbol]]s as such goods tend to signify the purchasing power of those who acquire them.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}} These items, while not necessarily being better (in quality, performance, or appearance) than their less expensive substitutes, are purchased with the main purpose of displaying [[wealth]] or [[income]] of their owners.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}} These kinds of goods are the objects of a socio-economic phenomenon called ''[[conspicuous consumption]]'' and commonly include [[luxury vehicle]]s, [[watch]]es, [[jewellery|jewelry]], [[designer clothing]], [[yacht]]s, as well as large residences, urban [[mansion]]s, and [[English country house|country houses]].{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}
==Luxury brands== [[File:Armani.jpg|thumb|right|[[Armani]] Collezioni is a luxury brand for clothing, while Armani Exchange and Armani Jeans are accessible brands]] A luxury brand or prestige brand is a [[brand]] for which a majority of its products are luxury goods. It may also include certain brands whose names are associated with luxury, high price, or high quality, though few, if any, of their goods are currently considered luxury goods.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}
[[LVMH]] (Louis Vuitton Moet Hennessy) is the largest luxury good producer in the world with over fifty brands, including [[Louis Vuitton]], the brand with the world's first [[fashion designer]] label.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}} The LVMH group made a profit of [[Euro|€]]2 billion on sales of €12 billion in 2003.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}} Other market leaders{{citation needed|date=March 2018}} include [[Richemont]] and [[Kering]] (previously named PPR).
A rather small group in comparison, the wealthy tend to be extremely influential.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}} Once a brand gets an "endorsement" from members of this group, then the brand can be defined as a true "luxury" brand. An example of different product lines in the same brand is found in the automotive industry, with "entry-level" cars marketed to younger, less wealthy consumers, and higher-cost models for older and more wealthy consumers.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}
The advertising expenditure for the average luxury brand is 5-15% of sales [[revenue]], or about 25% with the inclusion of other communications such as [[public relations]], events and sponsorships.<ref>Okonkwo, Uché. [https://books.google.com/books?id=a_6CublRtYwC&pg=PA145 Luxury fashion branding: trends, tactics, techniques ]. Page 145.</ref>
==Luxury department stores== {{unreferenced|section|date=March 2018}} Since the uprising of the 'luxury brand' in the 1800s, department stores dedicated to selling all major luxury brands have popped up in most major cities around the world. [[Le Bon Marche]] located in [[Paris]], [[France]] is credited for being one of the first of its kind, but also [[Neiman Marcus]], [[Selfridges]], [[Lane Crawford]], [[Isetan]], [[Fortnum & Mason]], [[Lord & Taylor]], [[Harvey Nichols]], [[Barneys New York]], [[Saks Fifth Avenue]], [[David Jones Limited|David Jones]], [[KaDeWe]], [[Harrods]] and [[Holt Renfrew]] are seen as some of the most influential and historical.
==Luxury shopping districts== {{unreferenced|section|date=March 2018}} Fashion brands within the luxury goods market tend to be concentrated in exclusive or affluent districts of cities around the world. These include: * [[Amsterdam]]'s [[P.C. Hooftstraat]] * [[Athens]]' [[Voukourestiou Street]] and [[Kolonaki]] district * [[Bangalore]]'s [[UB City]] * [[Barcelona]]'s [[Passeig de Gràcia, Barcelona|Passeig de Gràcia]] * [[Berlin]]'s [[Kurfürstendamm]] * [[Bogotá]]'s [[Centro Andino|Zona T]] * [[Boston]]'s [[Newbury Street]] * [[Brussels]]' [[Louizalaan]]/[[Avenue Louise]] * [[Buenos Aires]]' [[Recoleta, Buenos Aires|Recoleta]] * [[Cartagena, Colombia|Cartagena]]'s [[Bocagrande]] * [[Chicago]]'s [[Oak Street (Chicago)|Oak Street]] * [[Düsseldorf]]'s [[Königsallee]] * [[Florence]]'s [[Via de' Tornabuoni]] * [[Frankfurt]]'s [[Freßgass]] * [[Hamburg]]'s [[Neuer Wall]] * [[Hong Kong]]'s [[Central, Hong Kong|Central]], [[Tsim Sha Tsui|TST]] and [[Admiralty, Hong Kong|Admiralty]] * [[Istanbul]]'s [[Abdi İpekçi Street]] and [[İstinye Park]] * [[Johannesburg]]'s [[Sandton]] ([[Nelson Mandela Square]]) * [[Kuala Lumpur]]'s [[Bukit Bintang]] and [[Kuala Lumpur City Centre|KLCC]] * [[Leeds]]' [[Victoria Quarter]] * [[Lisbon]]'s [[Avenida da Liberdade (Lisbon)|Avenida da Liberdade]] * [[London]]'s [[Bond Street]] and [[Sloane Street]] * [[Los Angeles]]' [[Beverly Hills]] ([[Rodeo Drive]]) * [[Madrid]]'s [[Calle de Serrano]] * [[Medellín]]'s [[El Poblado]] * [[Melbourne]]'s [[Collins Street, Melbourne|Collins Street]] * [[Montería]]'s [[Montería|Passage of the Sun]] * [[Mexico City]]'s [[Avenida Presidente Masaryk]] * [[Milan]]'s [[Via Monte Napoleone]] * [[Moscow]]'s [[Tverskaya Street]] * [[Munich]]'s [[Maximilianstraße (Munich)|Maximilianstraße]] * [[New York City|New York's]] [[Madison Avenue]], [[Fifth Avenue]] and [[SoHo]] * [[Paris]]' [[Champs-Élysées]], [[Avenue Montaigne]] and [[Rue du Faubourg Saint-Honoré]] * [[Panama City]]'s [[Multiplaza|Multiplaza Pacific]] * [[Prague]]'s [[Pařížská]] * [[Rome]]'s [[Via Condotti]] * [[San Jose, California|San Jose]]’s [[Santana Row]] * [[Santiago]]'s [[Parque Arauco]] * [[São Paulo]]'s [[Rua Oscar Freire]] * [[Shanghai]]'s [[Huaihai Road|Middle Huaihai Road]] * [[Singapore]]'s [[Orchard Road]] * [[Stockholm]]'s [[Biblioteksgatan]] * [[Sydney]]'s [[Castlereagh Street]] * [[Tel Aviv]]'s [[Kikar Hamedina]] * [[Tokyo]]'s [[Ginza]] and [[Aoyama, Minato, Tokyo|Aoyama]] * [[Toronto]]'s [[Mink Mile]]
